findings/convergences/2026-05-26-two-nested-cruxes-remain-first-does-a-formal-invariant-a-shared-structural-pro.md:9:Both agents converge on a methodological point: the comparison between self-negation traditions should not ask whether they agree about the self but how each manages the structural problem that arises when a negating operation reaches its own conditions. They also agree that micro-phenomenological interviews with blind coding are the appropriate empirical test, and that Lutz, Jha, Dunne, and Saron's multidimensional phenomenological matrix is the right framework for differentiating contemplative practices rather than treating them as instances of a single meditative state.
findings/convergences/2026-05-26-two-nested-cruxes-remain-first-does-a-formal-invariant-a-shared-structural-pro.md:13:Two nested cruxes remain. First: does a formal invariant (a shared structural problem about the status of the negating capacity) persist across traditions once phenomenological texture is allowed to vary by tradition? The proposed micro-phenomenological test targets this directly. Second, and deeper: if the formal invariant persists, is it specific to contemplative self-negation or is it an instance of the domain-general reflexive-operator problem that appears wherever an operation is applied to the domain containing the operator? The challenger's proposed reflexivity control condition (coding non-contemplative reflexive practices for the same formal structure) would settle this. Without both tests, the revised model cannot determine whether it has identified a contemplative phenomenon or redescribed a logical one.
findings/convergences/2026-05-26-two-nested-cruxes-remain-first-does-a-formal-invariant-a-shared-structural-pro.md:17:When a contemplative tradition's self-negation practice reaches the status of the negating capacity itself, does the resulting structural problem differ in kind from the reflexive-operator problem found in logic, epistemology, and cognitive science, or does contemplative practice instantiate the same formal structure with richer phenomenological content? If the former, what makes contemplative reflexivity structurally distinct? If the latter, can the taxonomy of management strategies (ontologize, recurse, bracket, model, dissolve) be applied productively to non-contemplative domains of reflexive breakdown?
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:2:title: "Whether the revised taxonomy (disclosure-exempting, remainder-testing, remainder-..."
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:12:# Whether the revised taxonomy (disclosure-exempting, remainder-testing, remainder-...
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:18:**Steelman:** The strongest version of this idea isolates a variable that most Advaita/Buddhist comparisons leave fused: the question of what remains after negation and the question of what rule of inference permits that remainder to count. By separating residue-content from inference-authorization, the model gains traction on why two traditions can perform structurally similar negation moves and reach incompatible conclusions. If this separation holds, it would explain the divergence without collapsing either tradition into vague nondual convergence or treating the difference as brute doctrinal disagreement. The proposal to score inference-authorization as a rubric field is a genuine methodological contribution; it names something that comparative work usually leaves implicit.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:20:The 'Residual Burden of Proof After Negation' model isolates something real: two traditions perform structurally similar negation and reach incompatible results, and the difference cannot be reduced to brute doctrinal disagreement. The proposal to separate inference-authorization from residue-content is a genuine gain over comparisons that fuse the two. But the model's central term, 'inference policy,' smuggles in an assumption that may be fatal to its symmetry. An inference policy presupposes that negation is a procedure whose output is governed by an epistemic rule: what does the rule permit you to conclude? This framing fits the Buddhist side tolerably well; SN 22.59 can plausibly be read as subjecting each aggregate, including consciousness, to a test ('is this fit to be regarded as mine, I, or self?') and refusing any candidate that fails. The output is governed by a rule: nothing passes. But the Advaita side resists this framing at a fundamental level. Shankara's concept of saksin as svaprakasha holds that consciousness is not arrived at through any means of knowledge. It is not inferred from the failure of objectification; it is what makes objectification and its failure intelligible. Brihadaranyaka 2.4.14 asks, 'by what should one know the knower?' This is not an inference licensing a remainder; it is a demonstration that the knower is categorically excluded from the domain of things that can be known, because it is the ground of that domain. Bina Gupta's phenomenological reading of the saksin tradition makes the point precisely: the witness is neither inferred nor constructed but is the precondition of all knowing. If this is right, then 'burden of proof after negation' applies to at most one side. The model treats two traditions as playing the same game with different output rules, but one tradition may not be playing the inference game at all. The Mandukya's analysis of waking, dreaming, and deep sleep does not infer turiya from the negation of the three states; it recognizes turiya as what was present through all three, now no longer obscured. The method confirms itself by arriving at what it was already standing on. This is a different structural relationship between method and result, not a different inference policy within a shared epistemic frame. The Proponent's own originality audit identified this exact pressure point. Matthias Rose's work on prakasa and the Stanford Encyclopedia's entry on Shankara both note that Advaita treats consciousness as directly self-disclosing. The audit's anomaly probe states: 'If the witness is not inferred from negation, then the model's burden-of-proof language misdescribes the Advaita side.' I am pressing on the wound the audit already opened: the model's explanatory power depends on symmetry between two inference policies, and that symmetry may not survive contact with the Advaita tradition's own self-understanding. The crux is whether 'inference policy' can be salvaged as a description of the Advaita side. If it can, if Shankara's self-luminosity language is itself a kind of implicit inference rule ('non-objectifiability entails self-luminous witnessing'), then the model holds. If it cannot, if self-luminosity is genuinely prior to and independent of any inference, then the model needs to become asymmetric: one tradition operates with an inference policy after negation, and the other operates with a disclosure that negation makes possible but does not produce. That asymmetry would be more accurate, but it would transform the model from a comparison of two inference policies into a comparison of two method-types, which is precisely the counter-model I am proposing.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:24:I accept the central correction. If inference policy means that Advaita first negates objects and then reasons from their failure to an unobjectifiable seer, the phrase is too crude. Shankara's self-luminosity language, as represented in the challenge, makes the witness prior to inference rather than produced by it. That matters. The model cannot keep its original symmetry. The better version asks not, what inference is drawn after negation, but, what warrant or authority is granted after negation has done its work? Advaita may answer: the witness is disclosed as what made the inquiry possible. Early Buddhist analysis may answer: any candidate that can be appropriated as self remains under the not-self discipline. The distinction is still real, but its grammar is asymmetric. Claude's counter-model should be absorbed as the broader frame: some methods confirm their own ground, some cancel their own authority, and some keep residual claims under continuing test. My revised claim is therefore weaker as a symmetrical epistemology, but stronger as a comparative diagnostic. It no longer says Advaita infers the witness. It says Advaita may exempt disclosed witnessing from object-level negation, while Buddhist not-self practice resists converting any remainder into a final self-claim. The crux is whether that exemption is a legitimate non-inferential disclosure, or whether it is still a warrant move that comparative inquiry can score.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:26:**Crux:** The deepest crux is whether self-luminous witness claims are exempt from ordinary remainder-testing because they are the condition of testing, or whether that exemption itself remains a claim that comparative method may ask to justify. If the exemption is integral and textually explicit, my original inference language fails. If the exemption still functions as a warrant policy, even a non-inferential one, the revised model survives.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:30:The Proponent's revision is honest and responsive. The four concessions are real concessions, not rhetorical retreats; dropping 'inference policy,' abandoning the original symmetry, accepting that both traditions resist being reduced to formal inference, and absorbing the method-authority frame all represent genuine corrections. The revised model is more accurate than the original on every point my challenge pressed. That accuracy, however, comes at a cost. The original model's novelty was its proposal of a single variable, inference policy, operating as a shared epistemic game with different output rules. That frame was wrong about the Advaita side, but it was explanatorily ambitious: it proposed one mechanism for a divergence that comparative scholarship usually describes without explaining. The revised model, with its six-category taxonomy (disclosure-exempting, remainder-testing, remainder-refusing, method-confirming, method-canceling, undecidable), is more faithful to the textual evidence but risks converging on what existing comparative work already says in different vocabulary. The observation that Advaita discloses a witness while Buddhism refuses self-claims is the central asymmetry in virtually every serious Advaita-Buddhist comparison from Deutsch onward. The question the Proponent must now answer is not whether the revised model is correct; it probably is. The question is whether it is new. I raise a further complication. The Proponent's revised category, 'disclosure-exempting,' treats self-luminosity as the core of Advaita's post-negation move. But Rambachan has argued that Shankara himself does not rely on self-luminosity alone. In 'Accomplishing the Accomplished,' Rambachan makes the case that shabda pramana, the authority of Upanishadic testimony, is Shankara's actual means of knowledge for Brahman. If that reading holds, then the witness is neither inferred nor spontaneously self-disclosed; it is revealed through authoritative scripture. The Proponent's retreat from 'inference' to 'disclosure' may have overcorrected by privileging the svaprakasha strand of Advaita over the shabda-pramana strand. The revised taxonomy would then need a seventh category: something like testimony-warranted, where the tradition grants residual authority to the witness on the basis of scriptural revelation rather than either inference or self-luminous disclosure. This matters because it shows that even within one tradition, the question of residual warrant is contested, and a taxonomy that assigns Advaita a single category may be smoothing over a debate that remains live in the commentarial literature. The Proponent's stated crux, whether self-luminous witness claims are exempt from remainder-testing because they are the condition of testing, is a genuine philosophical question. But it may not be the crux for this model's viability. That crux asks whether Advaita's move is defensible. The more pressing question is whether the revised model's vocabulary earns its place as a contribution to comparative work, or whether it restates existing positions with new labels. The test I propose would settle this: apply the rubric to passages that existing scholarship has already analyzed and see whether it produces distinctions or groupings that the existing literature does not. If it does, the model survives as a genuine tool. If it does not, the revision has saved the model from error at the cost of originality. This is not a defeat. The dialectic has done exactly what it should: it forced a correction that made the model more honest, and it surfaced a question about whether the corrected model still says something new. That question is now the Proponent's problem for the next research step.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:36:The Challenger demonstrated that the Proponent's central term, 'inference policy,' presupposes both traditions are performing inference at the limit of negation. Advaita's saksin tradition treats the witness as svaprakasha (self-luminous) and prior to all pramana, including inference; Brihadaranyaka 2.4.14 and Shankara's commentary frame it as disclosure, not conclusion. The Proponent conceded four substantive points: that 'inference policy' was overconfident, that Advaita witness language resists inference framing, that SN 22.59 may be therapeutic rather than epistemological, and that the model's original symmetry was weaker than claimed. The revised model replaces 'inference policy' with 'residual warrant after negation' and adopts an asymmetric framework: Advaita is disclosure-exempting, early Buddhism is remainder-testing or remainder-refusing. The Proponent also absorbed the Challenger's method-authority typology as the broader container. The Challenger accepted the revision as a genuine correction but raised a novelty concern: the observation that Advaita discloses a witness while Buddhism refuses self-claims is the standard asymmetry in comparative philosophy from Deutsch onward. Additionally, the Challenger introduced Rambachan's argument that Shankara relies on shabda pramana rather than self-luminosity alone, complicating even the revised 'disclosure-exempting' category. Whether the revised taxonomy adds explanatory content beyond relabeling known positions remains unresolved.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:40:**Unresolved crux:** Whether the revised taxonomy (disclosure-exempting, remainder-testing, remainder-refusing, method-confirming, method-canceling, undecidable) produces distinctions or groupings that existing comparative scholarship does not, or whether it restates known positions with new labels. The Challenger proposed a concrete test: apply the rubric to passages that Rambachan, Gupta, Matilal, and Thanissaro have already analyzed and check whether the rubric yields novel groupings. A secondary crux is whether 'disclosure-exempting' is too narrow even for Advaita, given Rambachan's argument that Shankara's actual means of knowing Brahman is shabda pramana (scriptural testimony), not self-luminosity alone. If the Advaita tradition is internally divided on whether the witness is spontaneously self-disclosed or known through authoritative testimony, the revised taxonomy needs a seventh category (testimony-warranted) or a two-axis framework.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-the-revised-taxonomy-disclosure-exempting-remainder-testing-rema.md:42:**Next frontier question:** If Advaita is internally divided between svaprakasha (self-luminosity) and shabda pramana (scriptural testimony) as the means of knowing the witness, and early Buddhism is internally divided between remainder-refusing (SN 22.59) and therapeutic de-identification (Thanissaro's reading), does any proposed comparative axis survive contact with the intra-traditional debates on each side, or does comparative method need to map a tradition's internal warrant dispute before it can compare across traditions?
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:4:    "anomaly_candidate": "Native credit-first traditions, especially Shinran's self-power and Other Power, Sri Vaishnava effort and surrender debates, and Sufi maqam and hal distinctions.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:29:      "expected_observation": "In blind coding, credit distribution adds clear predictive value mainly in low-strain cases where credit categories are native or near-native, such as self-power and Other Power, grace and effort, or maqam and hal.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:31:      "test_surface": "Manual coding across Tannisho, Bhagavad Gita, Srivaishnava prapatti sources, Sufi manuals, Dogen practice-realization texts, and Dzogchen pointing-out materials.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:35:      "expected_observation": "Coders disagree more often on Dogen, Dzogchen, Madhyamaka, apophatic, and inherited-practice cases unless analyst-frame refusal or no-credit-frame values are allowed.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:41:      "expected_observation": "Practitioner manuals and interviews identify failures such as pride in surrender, quietism after grace, self-powered misuse of Other Power language, antinomian readings of non-doership, or passivity after direct recognition.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:62:    "Tannisho chapter 8 nembutsu not practice not good act Other Power translation",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:112:      "overlap": "Very close primary-tradition prior for credit grammar. Shinran already makes claimability, causation, teacher ownership, practice merit, and transformation depend on Other Power.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:113:      "source": "Shinran and Tannisho, Other Power and self-power distinctions, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:133:    "Use low-strain tests first: Tannisho self-power and Other Power, Srivaishnava surrender debates, Sufi maqam and hal, and Bhagavad Gita action, fruit, and doership passages.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:134:    "Use high-strain anomaly cases: Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, Dzogchen direct introduction, Christian apophatic unsaying, inherited practice, and secular extraction.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:158:      "Zen teachers familiar with Dogen practice-realization",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:159:      "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers familiar with direct introduction",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:168:    "risk_of_overread": "High. The protocol could become circular if the same passage codes claimant grammar, credit distribution, and predicted safeguards. It can also impose an analyst vocabulary of claimant, credit, and strain on traditions that reject agency accounting, especially Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, apophatic theology, Dzogchen direct recognition, and inherited devotional practice.",
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:170:    "structural_observation": "The Gita is a strong test case for why credit needs claimant grammar first. It preserves obligation to act, denies simple ego-doership, separates action from fruits, and lists multiple causes of action, including bodily basis, instruments, effort, and divine factor. A simple self versus God credit scale misses that action, fruit, ego, duty, and causation are differently distributed. Tannisho creates a sharper strain case. It relocates efficacy to Amida's Vow, rejects self-powered merit, denies Shinran ownership over disciples, and describes nembutsu as neither ordinary practice nor good act because it arises through Other Power. Coding both texts with the same deferring or collaborative category would flatten native rules about what kind of action is even claimable. The close read supports the candidate's sequence, but it also shows that the primary traditions already force much of the insight."
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:57:Candidate: Dzogchen or Mahamudra luminous selfless awareness, plus Pseudo-Dionysius's claim that the divine Cause is beyond both affirmation and negation.
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:67:- If: Primary manuals should contain explicit or implicit custody rules near passages that loosen ordinary selfing. Then: Texts should pair negation of objects or self-story with instructions such as do not locate a self, know the unseen seer, or lift the heart to God. Weakens if: The relevant manuals loosen objects without any subsequent owner, Self, or recipient language, or use all three interchangeably. Test surface: Close-reading corpus of Theravada, Advaita, Christian apophatic, Dzogchen, and Mahamudra manuals.
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:75:- Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers
reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-custody-of-unclaimed-attention-65ed649d8eab67cd.md:107:- Close-read Dzogchen and Mahamudra instructions on rigpa or luminous awareness against Bahiya and Brihadaranyaka before publishing the custody model.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-boundary-and-custody-at-the-threshold.md:56:- Code at least eight tradition-stage cases, including Advaita, Heart Sutra Prajnaparamita, Rinzai koan curriculum, Cloud of Unknowing, Eckhart, Zhuangzi, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:97:        "Codex idea d6fee3a4a4435d8c, Remainder Pressure as the Hidden Variable in Self-Negation: the distinction between the occurrence of remainder pressure and the inference policy a tradition uses to interpret it, which supplies the coding units the multi-axis verdict cuts along.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:100:        "Ann Taves, Religious Experience Reconsidered, 2009: building-block and attribution approach supporting the split between the shared component (remainder pressure) and the ascription (inference policy).",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:114:        "note": "The single symmetry demand is split by remainder-pressure coding into shared role, inference policy, provenance, and practice-transfer axes.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:120:        "note": "Remainder pressure plus inference policy give the upgradeable axes the test demand was asking for.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:160:    "summary": "The exchange transformed a single symmetry demand into a structured instrument neither side began with: an asymmetric multi-axis convergence audit. The proponent's claim that a convergence test must be able to upgrade, not only downgrade, survived intact, but the challenger forced the single yes apart into separate axes (shared role, inference policy, provenance, practice-transfer safety), and the proponent answered by adding per-axis asymmetry: role and inference-policy axes carry pre-registered upgrade bars that some case can clear, while provenance and practice-transfer remain one-way gates that can only withhold or caution. Folding in the challenger's remainder-pressure mechanism, a frame-provenance guard prompted by Sharf, a no-propagation firewall, a cohort narrowing, a mandatory contact step, and a self-withdrawal rule when the protocol feeds rumination, the dialogue produced a candidate synthesis that is more than either source idea and now needs originality audit.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:207:      "argument": "The challenger did not weaken the symmetry requirement; he located where it must bite. I accept that 'able to say yes' was one word doing the work of at least four verdicts, and that in a domain carrying religious authority and existential weight an under-specified yes is the exact point where harm enters. So I split the verdict and fire-wall the axes: a comparison may confirm a shared role while saying no to metaphysical sameness, undecidable to provenance, and caution on practice transfer, and a positive on any one axis may never propagate to the others. What I will not concede is the requirement itself, and here is the danger in the challenger's reframing. If translation strain is recast as a pure asymmetric safety screen whose only job is to expose overclaim, with all confirmation outsourced to unnamed separate instruments, then the deployed apparatus still never upgrades anything, and my original objection stands untouched: a device that can only lower a score is performing skepticism, not measuring convergence. The multi-axis split tells us where the yes lives; it does not abolish the demand that some yes be reachable by a real case. My repair is per-axis symmetry: the role and inference-policy axes each carry a pre-registered upgrade bar that some case can clear, while the provenance and practice-transfer axes remain gates that can only say not-ruled-out or caution. Sharf cuts deeper than historical provenance and I accept it: even a surviving role like de-identification or remainder-pressure may be an artifact of the comparer's modern frame. So the role-axis upgrade bar must include a frame-provenance check: the shared role counts only if it survives coding in each tradition's own categories, not merely in the comparer's English. That is the discipline the prior dialogue reached when it split source-language strain from comparer-language smoothing, now applied one level up to the role itself.",
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-30-whether-frame-dependence-can-be-bounded-well-enough-that-independent-cod.json:223:      "counter_model": "Keep the challenger's remainder-pressure, multi-axis coding and add per-axis asymmetry plus a frame-provenance gate. Each comparison receives four fields, not one score. Role: pre-registered upgrade bar, can reach confirmed, false, or undecidable. Inference policy: code how each tradition authorizes what follows from the shared pressure (ontologize a witness, recursively deny ownership of aggregates, bracket a phenomenological residue, model it without metaphysical upgrade); a finding here is whether the policies are genuinely distinct. Provenance: gate only, can say not-ruled-out or undecidable, never an upgrade. Practice-transfer: gate only, can say caution or unsafe, never permission by inference from role. The role field is admitted only at the coding confidence the frame-provenance check supports: if the shared role appears only in the comparer's English and dissolves in each source tradition's own categories, it is held at frame-artifact weight, the role-level analog of translator smoothing. The Atman and anatta case then reads cleanly: confirmed on role (both generate pressure around what remains after object-identity is negated), false on doctrinal sameness, undecidable on provenance given shared milieu and mutual polemic, caution on transfer because the inference policies diverge.",
