### Teaching Line

Do not turn a question the teaching refused into a path you must finish.

### Doctrine Claim

A self-negating or no-distance teaching should be read with the question it permits. When the practitioner imports a self-owned completion question, the teaching can become performance, withdrawal, or private certainty.

### Teaching Body

Some questions are useful: What must I practice? What did I learn? What should I repair? Other questions become heavy when a teaching has already taken them away. If a text, teacher, or practice says the self is not the owner, do not secretly make yourself the manager of that result.

Before you decide what an insight proves, ask whether the question belongs there. If the question asks you to perform, defend, or grade yourself, set it down for a moment. Return to one ordinary support that can correct you: a person, a promise, a task, a text, or rest.

A teaching that loosens ownership should make you more reachable and more honest, not more private and harder to interrupt.

### Human Problem

Burnout, loneliness, meaning loss, and achievement-contingent self-worth when spiritual or reflective practice becomes another private performance to manage.

### For

Stable reflective practitioners, meditation-app users, perfectionistic professionals, caregivers, students, founders, and self-improvers who turn rest, insight, or relief into self-grading.

### Pressure Survived

Survived critique pressure from Dogen, Shinran, Huangbo, and Dzogchen by treating them as limits on crossing questions rather than cases to force into one remainder map. Survived near-duplicate pressure by narrowing to the imported question as the tested failure variable.

### Falsifying Pressure

Weakens if no-distance and received paths do not preserve any discipline around permitted questions, if practitioner failures do not cluster around wrong-question imports, or if the teaching performs no better than ordinary rest, honest conversation, and social support.



## Practice Candidate

Status: seed
